  "slug": "fruit-scones-sultana",
  "title": "Fruit scones",
  "subtitle": "Sultana-studded afternoon-tea scones",
  "excerpt": "Twelve scones with a fine, even crumb and golden tops, made with cold butter rubbed in by hand and brought together with cold buttermilk in eight strokes. Sultanas swell into the crumb and give sweetness without sugar.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: the basic scone formula: flour, butter, milk, a raising agent. Florence White, Good Things in England (1932): the sultana addition and the no-twist cutter instruction.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The scone rule that matters most is also the one most often ignored: bring the dough together in as few strokes as possible. Eight is the number. Ten is acceptable. Twenty is too many. Over-mixing develops the gluten and produces a tight, dense scone instead of the loose, layered one the recipe intends.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The other rule is the cutter: press straight down. No twist. A twist seals the cut edges together and prevents the scone from rising evenly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
